# Bibliography Management Rules

Rules for maintaining the bibliography. See also `references.mdc` for BibTeX format and citation key conventions.

## Folder structure

- **Root:** `bibliography/` (no longer `papers/`).
- **Subfolders:** One per topic or theme (e.g. `math-and-cs/`, `interdisciplinarity/`, `philosophy-of-technology/`). Use subfolders so the bibliography can grow without a single flat list. **Every subfolder must contain a `.gitignore`** that excludes PDFs: add a file `bibliography/<subfolder>/.gitignore` with the single line `*.pdf`.
- **Per-paper files** live in the chosen subfolder: `{citationkey}.pdf`, full-text conversion (`{citationkey}.md` or fallback `{citationkey}.txt`), and the note file `{citationkey}-notes.md`.

Citation keys follow `references.mdc` (e.g. `commelin2023`, `orourke2016`). **PDFs should be renamed to `{citationkey}.pdf`** so that the same base name is used for all derived files in that subfolder.

**File naming:**

| File | Purpose |
|------|--------|
| `{citationkey}.pdf` | Source PDF (or EPUB; convert to PDF first if using pandoc on PDF). |
| `{citationkey}.md` | **Preferred:** Full text of the paper in Markdown, converted from PDF/EPUB via **pandoc**. Use when pandoc is available and succeeds. |
| `{citationkey}.txt` | **Fallback:** Plain-text extraction via **pdftotext** when pandoc is not used or fails (e.g. scan-only PDFs). |
| `{citationkey}-notes.md` | Our note file: metadata, summary, relevance to class, key concepts, reading notes (see structure below). |

Assistants and tools should prefer reading `{citationkey}.md` when present (better structure, headings); use `{citationkey}.txt` only when `.md` does not exist.

**Note on PDF and pandoc:** Pandoc does **not** support PDF as input. For PDF sources: (1) run `pdftotext bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.pdf bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.txt`; (2) then run `pandoc -f markdown -t markdown --wrap=none bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.txt -o bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.md`. The pandoc step turns pdftotext’s line-by-line output into one line per paragraph (blank lines stay as paragraph breaks). For EPUB or HTML/LaTeX sources, use pandoc directly to produce `.md`.

**Why `-notes.md` for the summary/note file:** With `.md` reserved for pandoc output (full text in Markdown), the human-written file (summary, relevance, key concepts, reading notes) needs a distinct name. `{citationkey}-notes.md` keeps the citation key first for sorting and makes the role clear in directory listings. Alternative: `{citationkey}.notes.md` if you prefer the "extension" style (all `{citationkey}.*` files group together).

## Adding a new paper

1. **Choose or create a subfolder** under `bibliography/` (e.g. `bibliography/math-and-cs/`).
2. **Add BibTeX entry** to `references.bib` (format and citation key: see `references.mdc`).
3. **Add entry to the subfolder README:** `bibliography/<subfolder>/README.md` (single-line bullet; see format below).
4. **Create the note file** in that subfolder: `bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}-notes.md` (structure below).
5. **Add PDF and full text:**
   - Save or copy the PDF into the subfolder, then **rename it to `{citationkey}.pdf`** (e.g. `romeo2024.pdf`). Do not leave journal filenames (e.g. `S0273-0979-2024-01819-9.pdf`) in place.
   - **Preferred — pandoc (Markdown):** `pandoc bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.pdf -o bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.md` (optionally add `--wrap=none` or extract only text: `pandoc ... -t markdown-smart`). For EPUB: `pandoc bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.epub -o bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.md`.
   - **Fallback — pdftotext then pandoc:** if the source is PDF only: `pdftotext bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.pdf bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.txt`, then `pandoc -f markdown -t markdown --wrap=none bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.txt -o bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.md` (so `.md` has one line per paragraph). Use `.txt` only when `.md` was not produced.
6. **Optionally update top-level index:** `bibliography/README.md` (list of subfolders and short description; link to each subfolder's README).

PDFs are ignored by git (e.g. via `bibliography/*/.gitignore` or root `.gitignore`). `.md`, `.txt`, and `-notes.md` are committed so assistants can use them.

## Subfolder README format

Each subfolder has a `README.md` that lists its papers as **single-line bullet points**:

```
- {Title} - {Author1} & {Author2} ({Year}) - [PDF]({url}) - [Scholar](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q={title-as-query}) - [`{citationkey}`]({citationkey}-notes.md)
```

- Title: full title, sentence case.
- Authors: use "&" between names, "Lastname & Lastname" (no first names in README).
- Year: 4-digit in parentheses.
- Link: `[PDF](url)` if available; otherwise omit or use [arXiv](…), [Website](…), etc.
- **Google Scholar:** `[Scholar](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q={title-as-query})` — use the paper title as the query string; spaces become `+`.
- Note file: `` [`citationkey`](citationkey-notes.md) ``.

Example:

```
- Abstraction boundaries and spec driven development in pure mathematics - Commelin & Topaz (2023) - [PDF](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2309.14870.pdf) - [Scholar](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Abstraction+boundaries+and+spec+driven+development+in+pure+mathematics) - [`commelin2023`](commelin2023-notes.md)
```

## Top-level bibliography index (optional but recommended)

`bibliography/README.md` can list subfolders so the structure scales:

- Brief description of each subfolder (e.g. "Math and CS convergence", "Interdisciplinarity").
- Link to each subfolder's README: `[math-and-cs](math-and-cs/README.md)`.

This gives a single place to see all topics and jump to the right subfolder when adding or searching papers.

## Note file structure (`{citationkey}-notes.md`)

Each note file in a subfolder should follow this structure:

```markdown
# {Title}

**Authors:** {Full names}
**Year:** {Year}
**Citation key:** `{citationkey}`
**PDF:** [link](url)
**arXiv:** [id](abs url)   (if applicable)
**Google Scholar:** [Search](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q={title-as-query})
## Summary

{2–3 paragraph summary of main contributions and arguments}

## Authors

{Short biographical paragraph for each author: institutional affiliation, key research areas, notable contributions, relevant background. Include links when available: [Homepage](url) | [Wikipedia](url) | [Google Scholar](url)}

## Relevance to our class

...

## Key concepts

...

## Notes

{Quotes, reading notes, follow-ups}
```

- Include the **citation key** used in `references.bib`.
- Include a **Google Scholar** link so you can quickly find citations and related work. The link must use the **paper title as the query string** in the URL (e.g. `https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Title+Of+Paper`); spaces in the title become `+`. Optionally append first author and year (e.g. `...+Author+Year`) for disambiguation.
- If there is an **open-access PDF**, link it in the note and optionally in the BibTeX entry (see `references.mdc`).

## Required actions when adding a paper

1. **Metadata:** Title, authors, year, PDF/arXiv URL from the source.
2. **BibTeX:** Add entry to `references.bib`; if open-access PDF exists, add `url = {\url{...}}`; use `note` only for text that should appear in the reference list; use `title = {{Title}}` with double braces to preserve capitalization.
3. **Subfolder:** Pick or create a subfolder under `bibliography/`.
4. **PDF:** Save to the subfolder and **rename to `{citationkey}.pdf`** (e.g. `harris2024.pdf`). Do not leave source filenames (e.g. publisher article IDs) in place.
5. **Full text:** For PDF: `pdftotext bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.pdf bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.txt`, then `pandoc -f markdown -t markdown --wrap=none bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.txt -o bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.md`. For EPUB/HTML/LaTeX: `pandoc bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.epub -o bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}.md` (and similarly for other formats pandoc supports).
6. **Subfolder README:** Add one bullet line in `bibliography/<subfolder>/README.md` (include PDF link, Google Scholar link with paper title as query, and note file link to `{citationkey}-notes.md`).
7. **Note file:** Create `bibliography/<subfolder>/{citationkey}-notes.md` with metadata, summary, relevance, key concepts, and notes; include a Google Scholar link with the paper title as the query string.
8. **Relevance:** Map paper content to topics in class.

## Scaling with many papers

- **Subfolders:** Add new subfolders by theme (e.g. `formalization/`, `philosophy-of-science/`) instead of piling everything in one list.
- **Subfolder README:** Stays one line per paper; no need for long descriptions in the README.
- **Note files:** Keep the detailed content in the `.md` files; README is only for discovery and links.
- **Top-level index:** Maintain `bibliography/README.md` with subfolder names and links so you can quickly see all topics.
- **Naming:** Use `{citationkey}.pdf` for the source; `{citationkey}.md` (pandoc) or `{citationkey}.txt` (pdftotext fallback) for full text; `{citationkey}-notes.md` for the note file. Rename PDFs to `{citationkey}.pdf` when adding papers; do not leave publisher or journal filenames in place.

## Git and file handling

- **PDFs:** Ignored by git (e.g. `*.pdf` in `bibliography/*/.gitignore` or equivalent). Stored locally only.
- **Full text and notes:** `{citationkey}.md`, `{citationkey}.txt`, and `{citationkey}-notes.md` are tracked so assistants and tools can search and summarise. Prefer `.md` (pandoc output) over `.txt` when both exist.
- This keeps the repo small while leaving full text available locally and in notes.

